          "body": "The liturgical section (vv. 1-16) is structured around two recurring phrases: 'according to the word of the LORD by Moses' (35:6, 12) and 'according to the command of King Josiah' (35:10, 16). The Chronicler is making a precise theological point: royal authority and Mosaic authority are in perfect alignment. Josiah does not improvise or legislate new forms; he restores what was written. The Levites are repositioned from carriers of the ark (now permanently housed in Solomon's temple, 35:3) to teachers and ministers of the sacrifice. Each guild — priests, Levites, singers, gatekeepers — occupies its appointed station (35:10, 15). The singers of Asaph stand at their posts according to the command of David, Asaph, Heman, and Jeduthun (35:15), reaching back through three centuries of musical tradition. This is the Chronicler's vision of ordered worship: Scripture-governed, historically anchored, and executed with meticulous care."
